[38;5;141m> [0m{"verdict": "pass", "rationale": "The Python companion uses correct boto3 patterns for Bedrock, DynamoDB, EventBridge, CloudWatch, Firehose, S3, and Secrets Manager (boto3.client/resource with Config-based adaptive retries, Table.get_item/put_item/update_item/query/delete_item, boto3.dynamodb.conditions.Key, put_events with Entries, put_metric_data with MetricData/Dimensions, put_record with DeliveryStreamName, put_object with SSE-KMS). Error handling is consistently wrapped in try/except with explanatory comments (DynamoDB float→Decimal note, EventBridge best-effort emit, CloudWatch best-effort metrics, ledger write resilience, partial-state lookup/write resilience, Firehose archive resilience). The code demonstrates the recipe end-to-end across all ten pseudocode steps—receive_message with input screening, encounter/chart/prior-intake context load and protocol selection, question-flow state machine with branching, per-category extraction tools (HPI, ROS, medication/allergy reconciliation, history, screener), parallel crisis-and-acuity flagging, crisis routing with reviewed templates, validated-screener administration with crisis-sensitive item handling, packet assembly and delivery with journaling, output safety screening with chart-fact integrity check, and durable audit archival via Firehose—exercised by run_demo across happy-path, crisis, and prompt-injection scenarios. The intake logic, state machine, extraction tools, crisis pipeline, screener scoring, and packet assembly are all fully implemented rather than stubbed; the in-memory Mock classes for AWS services and the EHR/registries are clearly labeled demo substitutes for runnability with extensive prose explaining the production gaps, consistent with the established pattern in recipes 11.1–11.3."}[0m[1G[0m[0m[?25h